rest_of_day_open: I see it being relaxing and low key after having accomplished a lot of my main priorities already this week. Mostly I'm going to just do some fun cooking and baking projects, maybe some yoga, watch a couple Ingmar Bergman movies (feeling strong enough to handle that level of darkness), and read This Side of Paradise.
critical_positive: He's smart / well educated in an area I'm not familiar with, which makes me immediately interested in a person and want to learn from them. He also started the conversation with a thoughtful question rather than the same old chit chat like "where are you from?". We both had insights to share and the conversation evolved naturally.
critical_negative: It would have been useful for me to have researched more about political polling in general, as it would have allowed for us to have a more evolved conversation about it. I also felt a slight hint of self doubt / insecurity once I learned he has a PhD, which may have affected my behavior in the rest of the conversation.

rest_of_day_open: I have the weekend to look forward to, and a socially distant outdoor meal with my sister and her family. That is a nice reprieve and break from the usual day-to-day grind of job applications. The next week looks like more of the same, though, so I'm going to try and savor the fun events this weekend.
critical_positive: Lots of synergy - I wouldn't say we had too many things in common, but my conversation partner was easy to talk too, was intelligent, and had a lot of stories to tell. It was very easy to float from one topic to another as well. Hence, why we spoke well past the 25 minute mark.
critical_negative: Not much to report on this front. We didn't have the same stock questions up front as my previous conversation partners: who are you, where do you live, etc. But once we got into the flow of conversation (which took a bit) it was easy to carry the conversation forward.
